                <head>320. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In his letter to President <persName corresp="#p_KJF1">Kennedy</persName>, April
                    29, 1963, (see <ref target="#d316">Document 316</ref>) Chairman <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> devoted several paragraphs to Cuba.
                    Regarding the Soviet military presence, he reiterated that the Soviets had
                    “withdrawn several times more people than has been stated in the American press.
                    How this matter will develop in the future depends on a number of circumstances
                    and in the first place on the pace at which the atmosphere in the region of the
                    Caribbean Sea will be normalized, and whether, as could be expected, the reasons
                    which occasioned the necessity for assistance to the Cubans by Soviet military
                    specialists and instructors will disappear.” For text, see <ref
                        target="frus1961-63v11#pg_791">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume XI, pages
                        791</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v11#pg_793">793</ref>.</p>
                <p>The next day, at a meeting of the National Security Council, Under Secretary of
                    State for Political Affairs <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>
                    reported on his talks on Cuba with <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                        >Khrushchev</persName> and Soviet Foreign Minister <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> in Moscow on April 25. According to the
                    summary record of the meeting, “<persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>
                    believes the Russians will go to great lengths to ensure that <persName
                        corresp="#p_CF1">Castro</persName> remains in control of Cuba. After Cuban
                    troops are trained, the Russian troops can be expected to leave, but Soviet
                    economic aid will be continued at a level necessary to ensure a going economy in
                    Cuba.” For text, see <ref target="frus1961-63v11#pg_795">ibid., pages
                        795</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v11#pg_797">797</ref>. The memorandum of
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>ʼs conversation with
                        <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> on April 25 is <ref
                        target="frus1961-63v11#pg_788">ibid., pages 788</ref>–<ref
                        target="frus1961-63v11#pg_791">791</ref>.</p>
